[[File:Wine bottle.JPG|thumb|right|A bottle showing the transparent green of many wine bottles]]
[[Image:Veuve clicquot bottle sizes.jpg|right|thumb|Side-by-side comparison of various sizes of champagne bottles (left to right), on the ladder: magnum, full, half, and quarter; on the floor: Balthazar, Salmanazar, Methuselah, and Jeroboam.]]

A '''wine bottle''' is a [[bottle]] used for holding [[wine]], generally made of [[glass]].  Some wines are [[fermentation (wine)|fermented]] in the bottle, others are bottled only after fermentation.

Recently, the bottle has become a standard unit of volume to describe sales in the wine industry, measuring {{convert|750|ml}}.{{fact|date=May 2012}}  However, bottles are produced in a variety of volumes and shapes.

Wine bottles are traditionally sealed with [[cork (wine)|cork]], but [[Screw cap (wine)|screw-top caps]] are [[Screw cap (wine)#Adoption|becoming popular]], and there are several [[alternative wine closures|other methods]] used to seal a bottle.<ref name="Johnson000">{{cite book
