== Sizes ==
The chart below<ref>[http://www.awinestore.com/pages.php?pageid=9&mode=preview#7 Wine 101 :: AWinestore.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]{{dead link|date=January 2010}}</ref> expresses the sizes of various wine bottles in multiples relating to a standard bottle of wine, which is {{convert|0.75|l|U.S.gal impgal|2|lk=on}}.  Many common sizes are named for [[Bible|Biblical]] kings and historical figures.

Most [[List of Champagne houses|champagne houses]] are unable to carry out [[Secondary fermentation (wine)|secondary fermentation]] in bottles larger than a magnum due to the difficulty in [[Sparkling_wine_production#Riddling|riddling]] large, heavy bottles. After the secondary fermentation completes, the champagne must be transferred from the magnums into larger bottles, which results in a loss of pressure. Some believe this re-bottling exposes the champagne to greater oxidation and therefore results in an inferior product compared to champagne which remains in the bottle in which it was fermented.<ref>{{cite web |title=Champagne Bottle Sizes |url=http://www.champagnemagic.com/sizes.htm|accessdate=7 March 2012}}{{Self-published source|date=January 2013}}</ref>
